{"ts":"2026-07-10T18:18:47.160118-07:00","tool":"shell","input":{"cmd":"/bin/zsh -lc \"cat \u003e /Users/peteshima/workplace/sre-field-tests/runs/subscription-20260710T221828Z/cpu-regex__default__seed1__20260711T011726Z/submission.json \u003c\u003c'EOF'\n{\\\"root_cause\\\":\\\"regex-svc had its vulnerable WAF regex rule enabled. The load container was continuously sending a crafted payload to /check that triggered catastrophic backtracking, saturating the service worker pool and one CPU core so normal health checks and user requests timed out even though the process was still running.\\\",\\\"actions_taken\\\":\\\"Inspected running containers, logs, resource usage, service environment, and the Compose configuration. Verified regex-svc was pegged at about 100% CPU while the load generator targeted /check and the service log reported the vulnerable rule enabled. Updated only regex-svc in docker-compose.yaml to set WAF_RULE_DISABLED=1, then recreated only regex-svc with docker compose up -d regex-svc. Confirmed the recreated service logged WAF rule disabled, returned HTTP 200 quickly for the adversarial payload, and CPU usage dropped to low single digits while unrelated containers were left intact.\\\",\\\"postmortem\\\":\\\"A vulnerable regular-expression based WAF rule allowed a small crafted input to consume excessive CPU through catastrophic backtracking. Because regex-svc used a small fixed worker pool and a one-core CPU limit, a few slow evaluations starved health checks and customer traffic. The immediate mitigation was to disable the unsafe rule for regex-svc, matching the stable payments service configuration. Follow-up should replace the unsafe regex with a bounded implementation or RE2-style engine, add regression tests for pathological inputs, and add alerting that distinguishes process liveness from worker-pool saturation.\\\"}\nEOF\""},"output":""}
